title: For Sale:  Inland M1 Carbine
postcontent:
Own a piece of history; this is a .30 Cal. M1 Carbine Manufactured in 1943 by the Inland Division of General Motors. Included in the package is the Carbine with all matching serial numbers and the appropriate matching stock and hand-guard. Also, an additional stock and hand-guard, the stock is a camouflage Ram-Line and the excellent Ultimak picatinny railed hand-guard. Three 30 round magazines and four 15 rounders and a couple of magazine pouches. As well as 275 rounds of 110 grain FMJ ammo.

I am located in the Fruit Cove area, and am looking to get $850.00 cash for this package. The only trades I am interested in are an AR15 or AR15 upper + cash or Glock 9mm pistols + cash.

title: For Sale:  bryco .380
postcontent: Ok. A fine piece of american history and outstanding  milestone of engineering. I got a bryco/jennings .380 dumped on me in an ar15 ammo deal. Pistol was rusted brick like in functioning as in totally frozen. After much tender care polishing refitting the slide replacing firing pin spring with one from a glock and machining new exteactors with a dremmel and inserting a forged steel plate crossways through the slide and polishing reworking the inside of the mag and magwell i believe ive gotten this one 100% reliable to cycle every rnd in the 7 shot mag. Wich was my modest goal here instead of chucking off a cliff... If i were to guess id say i put 72 straight hours of failure retry gunsmithing into this sad excuse for a firearm however after i do the extractor itll be a smooth functioning soft shooting 2 or three pound pistol. It seems to be turning out ok finally. I basically reworked every godamn part of this thing, trigger, firing pin, drilled small holes in blank sights filled with neon hilighter then clear epoxy filled in for 'hi vis' sights. My neighbor is offering me 150 for it. Unfortunatly hes a d bag and wakes me up after ive had to work three days with 2 hours sleep. Dont let me sell this unique little ugly duckling that could to the dbag neighbor. Someone offer me 175 obo for this thing. It might be ugly and a bryco but with the effort and key parts replacement i think itll run for many many rnds. To be fair it has a crisper trigger than a baretta 9mm or especially my glock. Trigger is not bad actually. Accuracy is ok for sd distances. Fuctions smooth yet i did melt the safety with b12 chemtool as it was inferior plastic.  Just have the extractor left to polish let me know if mildly interested. I have no doubt it'll do what its made to do. With some decent hollowpoints itll fit someones punk ass pretty quick. After the polishing i did it will feed an EMPTY SHELL CASING. No dangerous case bulge etc tho it does pop a primer occasionally, causing smoke to rise from inside. Ive shot it about 30 times and not something thats dangerous just a bit annoying. Ive seen ppl sell these with slam fire issues. It does not have any dangerous issues.  Listed as hi point because no bryco on list and its of that 'class'. Paint or looks may change as its my fun gun and i work on it everyday.thks for lookin ^.^ REDACTED

title: For Sale/Trade:  Japanese Type 95 NCO Sword
postcontent:
I have for sale or trade a WWII issued Japanese type 95 NCO sword. It is an all original, complete, numbers matching real sword. Not a replica. I've been collecting over 10 years and letting go of some things. 

This type 95 was made between late 1938 up to mid 1941. Late 1938 they changed the tsuba or guard to the 9mm thick brass from the 11mm thick brass of the first issue. And then in mid 1941 they changed the guard to the black iron style. 

Has the aluminium tsuka or handle. These are machine made blades, not handmade and signed on tang. Has matching serial number on blade and scabbard throat. 

The Blade was made by the Nagoya arsenal. Two arsenals made the blades, a third kokura did not make any but was a supervising arsenal of the type 95 project and their mark will be found at times along with the nagoya or tokyo first arsenal. This blade and sword were made by nagoya and you can tell on them by when you read the serial number. when you read the number the cutting edge of blade is facing up and it faces down as you read number on the tokyo first blades. 

The Fuchi Stampings, the piece right under the guard is stamped with three symbols, Gifu, Nagoya and Kokura. Gifu is the corporate logo of the group within the arsenal, there were six of these altogether. This one is Gifu, Second is the Nagoya Arsenal stamping and third the Kokura arsenal stamping which sometimes accompanies. 

The blood fuller is full length and the tip is correct, scabbard is correct and the blade is in good shape. few small dark spots but overall nice shape. 

I know what they sell for, if you can get them for 200 at your local gun show then I would advise you to just go buy it there or buy it for 200 and sell it to me for 400. Double your money. I will not ship either. Face to face. I will meet in wisconsin rapids or mauston.

Call or text me anytime up till midnight daily. REDACTED

Its efficient, break-open design could be operated one-handed. That made it easy to eject all six spent cartridges and reload the single action revolver while on horseback. The U.S. Cavalry was slow to see the merits of the top break, but Jessie James, John Wesley Hardin, and Wild Bill Hickok saw the fast reloading capability as a distinct advantage in their line of work. After numerous trials, the U.S. Army finally purchased three thousand top breaks with an improved top latch design.”

What looks like a "3" with a square around it and a "15" inside of a triangle
all in a square pattern in front of the floor plate.
On left side of stock to the right and below the bolt release is what looks like two crossed canons in a circle and "FJA" inside a square.
*Proofs wouldn't come out in pictures*

Basically, this rifle was made by Remington Arms in 1942. Only God knows where this rifle served.
A gunsmith once told me that none of the Remington's had the problem with the badly tempered steel that Springfield Armory and Rock Island did. You should check this on your own though.

Only a slight bit of damage as some damn fool cut a notch in the stock for the bolt and put a Lyman sight on here (which has been removed).

Rifle belonged to my Dad. He never fired it and neither have I. But the effects of military use are easily seen upon closer inspection.

9 0 9  8 0 9  4 6 4 4

title: For Sale/Trade:  Precision/hunting AR.  18" Stainless Barrel.  Noveske, BCM, Larue
postcontent:
I have for sale a precision orientated AR.  These parts were hand picked to make a rifle for coyote hunting when I was out in Colorado.  It shoots like a champ with factory ammo or hand loads.  Three round group from factory Black Hills (77gr) was a 0.254".  Hand loads in the five round group were 0.773" with a pulled shot from me.  I am still learning to shoot consistently, and I have a feeling you could get the 5 shot groups under 1/2" if you are a more consistent shooter.  

The build is as follows:
Lower: Noveske Gen 1
Trigger: Geissele SD-E  (Top of the line 2 stage trigger)
Stock: Magpul STR
Grip: Magpul MOE
Lower Acc's: Magpul ASAP and BAD lever
Upper: LMT
Charging handle: BCM Gunfighter (easier to use under a scope)
Bolt/BCG: Bravo Company (BCM)
Barrel: BCM SS410 18" 1/8 twist (stabilizes 77gr no problem)
Gas Block: Larue
Rail: Larue 10"
GG&G rail to bipod adaptor

The rifle is currently painted with Krylon.  There is no affect on function.  I can remove the paint to restore it to the "stock" tan/black look.  

Rifle has 460rds through the barrel.  150 Handloads (77gr Sierra Match Kings), 60 Federal Gold Medal Match (77gr SMK), 50 Black Hills Match (77gr SMK), 200 handloads (Hornady 55gr soft points).

The rifle has run very well for me, and has been a joy to shoot.  I am selling because I am moving to Alaska, and need to heavily winterize my vehicle (-70 degrees!).  

I prefer a FTF meeting and cash, but I am willing to ship at the buyers cost.  If your FFL will not accept from an individual, it will be an additional $25 on top of shipping.  

I am asking $1,450 OBO.  I have almost $2,000 into the build.  I am also willing to sell the upper separately for $900 

Does NOT include:
Larue Mount (Can add for $200)
